  "summary": "Inspector Japp informs Polly that a shooting incident occurred where a bullet intended for Alistair Blunt was missed, potentially targeting the Prime Minister instead. The perpetrator was an Indian student who was apprehended by an American man named Ricks, a patient who had previously escaped from Morley following a suicide.\n\nPoirot visits a Gothic front where he meets Mr. Selby, a secretary for Mr. Brent. Selby delivers an invitation from Mr. Brent for Poirot to join him for a weekend at his country house, Kensington. During the visit, Poirot encounters Mrs. Olivia, a fashionable woman who expresses displeasure at Poirot's invitation, claiming Mr. Brent wanted a quiet weekend with only his family. Mrs. Olivia's daughter, Jane, approaches Poirot privately and urgently whispers that the Countess of Morcerf is dead, pleading with him not to get involved. Poirot is unsettled when he hears Mrs. Olivia arguing with Jane, noting that her voice sounds identical to a voice he heard on the phone the previous night.\n\nThe following morning, a Rolls-Royce picks up Poirot for the trip. The vehicle contains only Alistair Blunt and his secretary. During the drive, Blunt dismisses the assassination attempt as the work of incompetent, idealistic students. He reveals that he had previously received an ineffective bomb through the mail. Blunt discusses his preference for common sense and simple arithmetic over complex philosophy or politics, eventually transitioning the conversation to Poirot's detective work.",
